  "text": "Since NF-kB is activated by PKC in several cell types [CITATION_1] , we next determined if M-CSF-induced NF-kB transcriptional activity was dependent on PKC activation and if calcium, a co-factor for conventional PKC isoform activation, was important. In addition, because of the number of conventional PKCs existing within mononuclear cells, pharmacological inhibitors of PKC family activation was used to determine the relationship of PKC activation to M-CSF-induced cellular survival. MDMs were transfected with the pNF-kB-SEAP reporter and then treated with the general PKC inhibitor, Ro-31-8220; the conventional PKCa/b inhibitor Gö-6976; or the intracellular calcium blocker BAPTA/AM. Ro-31-8220 significantly suppressed M-CSF-induced NF-kB activity compared to cells treated with M-CSF alone (Figure 2A ). In addition, Gö-6976 and BAPTA/AM also blocked NF-kB activity in M-CSF-treated MDMs. Trypan blue exclusion analysis did not indicate cell death suggesting that this suppression was not due to non-specific toxicity. These data indicate that M-CSF mediated NF-kB activation through calcium-dependent conventional PKC activation.",
